  "Sugar is a molecular solid held together by weak IMFs. It has no free electrons or mobile ions, making it an excellent insulator. Copper has delocalized electrons, graphite has delocalized pi electrons, and molten NaCl has mobile ions.": "",
  "What is the Clausius-Clapeyron equation used for?": "",
  "Determining crystal structure": "",
  "Calculating bond energy": "",
  "Relating vapor pressure to temperature through the enthalpy of vaporization": "",
  "Calculating the density of solids": "",
  "The Clausius-Clapeyron equation (ln(P₂/P₁) = -ΔH_vap/R × (1/T₂ - 1/T₁)) relates vapor pressure at different temperatures to the enthalpy of vaporization, allowing prediction of boiling points at different pressures.": "",
  "Which type of solid can conduct electricity in the solid state?": "",
  "Most molecular solids": "",
  "Covalent network solid (diamond)": "",
  "Metallic solids conduct electricity in the solid state because their delocalized electrons can flow freely. Ionic solids only conduct when melted or dissolved (ions must be mobile). Diamond is an insulator.": "",
  "What is the enthalpy of fusion (ΔH_fus)?": "",
  "The energy released when two nuclei fuse together": "",
  "The energy required to convert one mole of a solid to liquid at its melting point": "",
  "The energy to break all bonds in a solid": "",
  "The energy released when a gas condenses": "",
  "Enthalpy of fusion is the energy needed to melt one mole of a solid at its melting point. It is always less than ΔH_vap because melting only partially disrupts intermolecular forces while vaporization completely overcomes them.": "",
  "What is a 'crystalline solid'?": "",
  "A solid that has been grown in a laboratory, based on conventional assumptions about crystalline": "",
  "A solid that dissolves easily in water when considering all relevant crystalline factors": "",
  "Any solid that is transparent, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "A solid with atoms, ions, or molecules arranged in a highly ordered, repeating three-dimensional pattern (lattice)": "",
  "Crystalline solids have a regular, repeating arrangement of particles forming a crystal lattice. They have sharp melting points and may exhibit characteristic geometric shapes. Examples include salt, quartz, and metals.": "",
  "What does 'amorphous solid' mean?": "",
  "A solid that is always opaque, especially during periods of significant change": "",
  "A solid with a well-defined crystal structure, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "A solid with ionic bonds, since standard models of amorphous behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "A solid that lacks long-range order in its atomic arrangement, softening gradually rather than melting at a sharp temperature": "",
  "Amorphous solids have disordered particle arrangements without a repeating crystal lattice. They soften over a range of temperatures. Examples include glass, rubber, and many polymers.": "",
  "What is a 'covalent network solid'?": "",
  "A solid composed of discrete molecules held by weak forces": "",
  "A solid containing ionic bonds between atoms": "",
  "A solid where atoms are connected by a continuous network of covalent bonds throughout the entire structure": "",
  "A solid with delocalized electrons": "",
  "Covalent network solids have atoms bonded by covalent bonds in a continuous 3D network. There are no discrete molecules. Diamond (C), quartz (SiO₂), and silicon carbide (SiC) are examples with extremely high melting points.": "",
  "What does 'enthalpy of vaporization' (ΔH_vap) mean?": "",
  "The energy released when a liquid freezes": "",
  "The energy of the vapor above a liquid": "",
  "The difference in temperature between boiling and freezing points": "",
  "The energy required to convert one mole of liquid to gas at its boiling point": "",
  "ΔH_vap is the energy needed to vaporize one mole of a liquid at its boiling point. It is always positive (endothermic) and larger than ΔH_fus because vaporization completely separates molecules.": "",
  "What is a 'molecular solid'?": "",
  "A solid composed of metal atoms held by delocalized electrons": "",
  "A solid composed of discrete molecules held together by intermolecular forces (LDF, dipole-dipole, or hydrogen bonds)": "",
  "A solid with a continuous network of covalent bonds": "",
  "A solid composed of ions in a lattice": "",
  "Molecular solids consist of individual molecules held in a lattice by IMFs. They typically have low melting points and poor conductivity. Examples include ice, dry ice, and sugar.": "",
  "What does 'ionic solid' refer to?": "",
  "A solid that is always water-soluble": "",
  "A solid that conducts electricity in all states": "",
  "A solid composed of cations and anions held together by electrostatic attraction in a regular crystal lattice": "",
  "A solid made of neutral molecules arranged in a crystal": "",
  "Ionic solids contain alternating cations and anions in a 3D lattice. They have high melting points, are hard but brittle, conduct electricity only when melted or dissolved, and many are soluble in polar solvents.": "",
  "What is 'X-ray crystallography'?": "",
  "A method to measure the hardness of minerals in most scenarios involving atoms factors": "",
  "A technique that determines atomic arrangement in crystals by analyzing the diffraction pattern of X-rays passed through the crystal": "",
  "A method to melt crystals using X-rays according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "A way to create artificial crystals, as conventional atoms theory would suggest": "",
  "X-ray crystallography uses the diffraction of X-rays by the regularly spaced atoms in a crystal to determine the three-dimensional arrangement of atoms. It revealed the structures of DNA, proteins, and countless crystals.": "",
  "What does 'heating curve' represent?": "",
  "A graph of volume vs. temperature for a gas, particularly in the context of temperature": "",
  "A graph of pressure vs. temperature, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "A graph showing temperature change of a substance as heat is added at constant rate, including plateaus at phase transitions": "",
  "A graph of reaction rate vs. temperature without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "A heating curve plots temperature vs. heat added. Sloped regions show temperature increases within a phase (using specific heat). Flat plateaus show phase changes (using ΔH_fus or ΔH_vap) at constant temperature.": "",
  "What is 'specific heat capacity'?": "",
  "The amount of heat required to raise the temperature of 1 gram of a substance by 1°C": "",
  "The temperature at which a substance melts": "",
  "The total heat content of a substance": "",
  "The rate at which a substance heats up": "",
  "Specific heat capacity (c) is measured in J/(g·°C). Water has an unusually high specific heat (4.184 J/g·°C) due to hydrogen bonding, making it excellent for temperature regulation in biological and environmental systems.": "",
  "What does 'supercooling' mean?": "",
  "Cooling a substance to absolute zero": "",
  "Rapidly cooling a gas to form a solid": "",
  "Cooling a liquid below its freezing point without it solidifying, due to the absence of nucleation sites": "",
  "Adding a coolant to a chemical reaction": "",
  "Supercooling occurs when a liquid is cooled below its freezing point without crystallization. This happens when there are no nucleation sites for crystal formation. Adding a seed crystal or disturbing the liquid can trigger rapid crystallization.": "",
  "A materials engineer must select a material for a furnace lining that operates at 2000°C. She considers silicon carbide (SiC, covalent network, mp 2730°C), iron (metallic, mp 1538°C), and sodium chloride (ionic, mp 801°C). Why is SiC the best choice?": "",
  "SiC has metallic bonds that withstand heat": "",
  "SiC has the weakest bonds, making it most flexible": "",
  "SiC is a covalent network solid with strong, continuous Si-C bonds throughout, giving it an extremely high melting point above 2000°C": "",
  "All three materials would work equally well": "",
  "SiC's covalent network structure means breaking bonds requires disrupting the continuous 3D network of strong Si-C covalent bonds. Only network solids have melting points high enough for extreme temperature applications.": "",
  "A chocolatier knows that chocolate must be 'tempered' - carefully cooled to form the right crystal structure (Form V polymorph of cocoa butter). Improperly tempered chocolate has a dull appearance and crumbly texture. What does this reveal about the properties of molecular solids?": "",
  "Molecular solids always form only one crystal structure": "",
  "The crystal structure of molecular solids doesn't affect their properties": "",
  "Only ionic solids can exist in different crystal forms": "",
  "Some molecular solids can form multiple crystal arrangements (polymorphs) with different physical properties depending on how they crystallize": "",
  "Polymorphism occurs when the same molecules can pack into different crystal arrangements. Cocoa butter has 6 polymorphs. Form V gives the glossy appearance and snap of well-tempered chocolate, while other forms produce inferior texture.": "",
  "A geologist compares two minerals: diamond and graphite, both made of pure carbon. Diamond is the hardest natural material while graphite is so soft it's used as a lubricant. Both are covalent network solids. What structural difference explains their vastly different hardness?": "",
  "Diamond has more carbon atoms per unit volume due to the well-established relationship between diamond trends and broader outcomes": "",
  "Diamond has a 3D tetrahedral network (sp³) with strong bonds in all directions, while graphite has 2D sheets (sp²) with strong bonds within sheets but only weak London forces between sheets": "",
  "Diamond has stronger C-C bonds than graphite due to the well-established relationship between diamond trends and broader outcomes": "",
  "Graphite contains impurities that weaken it given that prevailing diamond conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "In diamond, every carbon is sp³ bonded to 4 neighbors in a rigid 3D network. In graphite, sp² carbons form strong hexagonal sheets, but sheets are held together by only weak LDF, allowing them to slide easily.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical company discovers that two crystalline forms of the same drug have different dissolution rates. Form A dissolves quickly and is effective, while Form B dissolves slowly and is less effective. Both are chemically identical. What phenomenon is this?": "",
  "Polymorphism - the same molecule packs into different crystal structures with different physical properties like solubility and dissolution rate": "",
  "Isomerism - the molecules have different structures, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "Degradation - Form B has partially decomposed when considering all relevant dissolution factors": "",
  "Allotropism - the atoms bond differently in most scenarios involving dissolution factors": "",
  "Polymorphism is critical in pharmaceuticals. Different crystal packings of the same molecule produce different lattice energies and surface properties, affecting dissolution rate, bioavailability, and shelf stability.": "",
  "An ice cream maker knows that adding salt to ice creates a bath cold enough to freeze cream (-15°C). She uses rock salt (NaCl). A colleague suggests using CaCl₂ instead. Why would CaCl₂ lower the freezing point more than NaCl at the same mass concentration?": "",
  "CaCl₂ is colder than NaCl, as the dynamics involved tend to push conditions in this direction over time": "",
  "CaCl₂ dissociates into 3 ions (Ca²⁺ + 2Cl⁻) per formula unit versus 2 for NaCl (Na⁺ + Cl⁻), producing more particles and greater freezing point depression": "",
  "CaCl₂ is more soluble but produces the same freezing point depression, based on conventional assumptions about Cacl": "",
  "CaCl₂ has stronger ionic bonds, although this interpretation oversimplifies the actual Cacl mechanisms at work": "",
  "Freezing point depression depends on the total number of dissolved particles (ΔT = iKfm). CaCl₂ produces 3 ions per formula unit (i = 3) versus 2 for NaCl (i = 2), giving ~50% more depression at the same molality.": "",
  "A glassblower heats ordinary window glass (SiO₂ with Na₂O and CaO additives) and notices it softens gradually over a range of temperatures rather than melting sharply. Quartz (pure SiO₂ crystal) has a sharp melting point of 1713°C. Why does window glass behave differently?": "",
  "Window glass undergoes sublimation instead of melting, as the dynamics involved tend to push conditions in this direction over time": "",
  "The additives in glass raise the melting point when the interaction between glass and window factors is taken into full account": "",
  "Window glass has weaker Si-O bonds because the underlying forces at work tend to produce exactly this type of outcome": "",
  "Window glass is an amorphous solid without long-range order, so different regions soften at different temperatures; crystalline quartz has a uniform structure with a defined melting point": "",
  "Window glass is amorphous (disordered). Na and Ca disrupt the SiO₂ network, preventing crystallization. Without a regular lattice, there's no single energy at which all bonds break simultaneously, so glass softens gradually.": "",
  "A student measures the time for water and ethanol to flow through a viscometer. Water takes 35 seconds and ethanol takes 18 seconds at the same temperature. Both have hydrogen bonding. Why is water more viscous?": "",
  "Water molecules are larger than ethanol molecules according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "Ethanol has stronger intermolecular forces, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "Water molecules are heavier than ethanol molecules under most circumstances involving water": "",
  "Water can form up to 4 hydrogen bonds per molecule in a 3D network, while ethanol can form only about 2, creating stronger resistance to flow in water": "",
  "Each water molecule can form up to 4 hydrogen bonds (2 donors, 2 acceptors), creating an extensive 3D network. Ethanol can form fewer H-bonds (only the -OH group), so its network is less extensive and it flows more easily.": "",
  "A meteorologist explains why coastal cities have milder temperatures than inland cities at the same latitude. This is called the 'maritime effect.' Which property of liquid water accounts for this climate moderation?": "",
  "Water's high specific heat capacity (4.184 J/g·°C) allows it to absorb and release large amounts of heat with minimal temperature change, moderating nearby temperatures": "",
  "Water evaporates faster near the coast considering that the key variables involved tend to move in this direction together": "",
  "Ocean currents bring warm water to all coastlines given that prevailing cities conditions tend to reinforce this particular trajectory": "",
  "Water's low density compared to land when the interaction between cities and coastal factors is taken into full account": "",
  "Water's exceptionally high specific heat (due to hydrogen bonding) means the ocean absorbs enormous energy in summer without heating much, and releases that energy in winter, keeping coastal temperatures mild.": "",
  "A forensic scientist finds an unknown white crystalline substance at a crime scene. She tests its properties: it does not conduct electricity as a solid, dissolves in water to form a conducting solution, has a high melting point, and is hard but brittle. What type of solid is it most likely?": "",
  "All properties match ionic solids: non-conducting as solid (ions locked in place), conducting when dissolved (ions mobile), high melting point (strong electrostatic lattice), hard but brittle (layer displacement causes repulsion).": "",
  "A home brewer adds priming sugar to beer before bottling. The dissolved CO₂ creates carbonation. She stores some bottles in the freezer and forgets them. The next day, several bottles have cracked and pushed out ice. Why did the bottles crack?": "",
  "Water expands when it freezes because the open hexagonal hydrogen-bonding structure of ice occupies more volume than liquid water, creating pressure that cracks the glass": "",
  "The glass contracted more than the liquid, since standard models of bottles behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "Dissolved sugar crystallized and expanded, which is consistent with how bottles mechanisms are understood to operate in theory": "",
  "The CO₂ gas expanded as it cooled, as the dynamics involved tend to push conditions in this direction over time": "",
  "Water is one of the few substances that expands upon freezing (~9% volume increase). The open hexagonal crystal structure of ice has more empty space than liquid water. This expansion in a sealed glass bottle generates enough force to crack it.": ""
